(vii)  review proposals for bus refuges and any access recommendations required to 
ensure operational safety; 
(viii)  review the earthworks balance for each road subcomponent and ensure that a minimum of surplus 
and/or deficit material is achieved; 
(ix)  in conjunction with the environment specialist, review proposals for excavating and/or disposing of road 
construction materials; 
(x)  in conjunction with the utility infrastructure services engineers, review the proposals for service ducts, 
culverts, manholes and chambers and their respective design parameters and their general suitability; 
also consider alternative options with associated costs to ensure an optimized solution is offered; 
(xi)  advise on appropriate road drainage works and bank protection (where appropriate) from rainfall runoff; 
(xii)  review the proposals for bridge designs and comment on the suitability of design parameters to be 
adopted; 
(xiii)  identify  opportunities  to  improve  and  implement  best  practice  approaches  to  public  transport 
operations, pedestrian, and NMT accessibility and movement in the project design; 
(xxvi)  assess  opportunities  and  feasibility  of  private  sector  participation  through 
performance-based contractual arrangements in public transport; 
(xiv)  work with the resettlement specialist to develop a project component design, which will minimize the 
number of affected people; 
(xv)  review geotechnical data on the ground conditions for roads and prepare terms of 
reference (TOR) for necessary surveys and investigations; 
(xvi)  review and prepare a road safety action plan; 
(xvii)  recommend  innovative  features  to  promote  low-carbon  development,  NMT,  and 
climate change resilience;  
(xviii)  recommend  associated physical  assistance  to enhance  road  safety  and  energy 
saving, such as intersection crossing safety measures, traffic monitoring system, 
solar-powered street lighting, etc.;  
(xix)  establish  baseline  and  performance  targets  for  impact,  outcome,  and  output 
indicators relating to roads component;  
(xx)  provide inputs on cost estimates, procurement plan, appropriate contract packaging, 
implementation  schedule,  bid  documents,  and  TORs  for  project  implementation 
consultants;  
(xxi)  propose capacity development program; 
(xxii)  assist the implementing agencies and design institutes to finalize the feasibility-level 
design  of  the  facilities  at  each  project  component,  together  with  layouts, 
calculations, cost estimates, and justification, based on existing studies and reports 
prepared by the executing agency; 
(xxiii)  prepare a procurement capacity assessment report in accordance with the ADB 
questionnaire and checklist; 
(xxiv)  prepare relevant sections of reports and assist with the auditing of TMG’s draft final FSR; and 
(xxv)  The consultant, together with the team leader and with the support of the executing agency, will be 
responsible for the organization of workshops. 

10.  Utilities services network modeller (1.0 person-month, international). The expert should 
be suitably qualified at professional level and have at least 12 years work experience in applying 
network models to water supply and sewerage systems. S/he will have a total input of 1 person-
month and will undertake at least the following duties: 

(i)  assess and comment on the completeness of the water supply network and sewerage 
system and their proposed integration with adjacent future phased developments in 
