the  Tacheng  Baktu  Liaota  New  Area;  and  recommend  changes  as  appropriate, 
members, Board of Directors, Management, or staff, and may be preliminary in nature.  
particularly with respect to water supply zones and district metering and, if applicable, 
sewage pumping operation;

14  Attachment  
(ii)  direct  and  assist  the  design  institute  to  establish  computer  network  models 
respectively for the water supply and sewerage networks to serve the Tacheng Baktu 
Liaota New Area; and ensure that the models are suitable for incorporating all other 
development areas forming the master plan of Baktu Liaota; and 
(iii)  provide  training  on  the  practical  application  and  benefits  of  network  modelling 
especially with respect to district metering, overall network performance monitoring, 
operation and maintenance, and investment need and planning. 

11.  Water and nonrevenue water management engineer (3.0 person-months, national). The 
expert should have relevant qualifications and about 10 years work experience in urban utility 
service engineering and planning. In support of the international municipal engineer and utility 
services network modeler the expert will perform the following tasks: 

(i)  review  and  assess  the  FSRs  for  the  subprojects,  mainly  the  aspects  of  water 
resource treatment and supply, and ensure that the subprojects are consistent with 
the municipal development programs, and environmental protection programs, and 
coordinate  with  other  urban  development,  pollution  control,  and  land  greening 
activities within the prefecture and city/town; 
(ii)  provide advice on cold and extremely dry weather engineering and impacts on designs and efficiencies 
of operation; 
(iii)  provide recommendations, where necessary, for obtaining and applying historic and 
predictive data to justify options under the proposed project scope;  
(iv)  review of parameters to be used in the design of the proposed water supply systems 
and recommend any changes deemed appropriate; 
(v)  investigate  and  assess  the  quantities  of  water  properly  used  by  the  domestic 
population,  commerce  and  industry,  and  for  internal  use  (including  flushing, 
firefighting, and the like), and the proportion discharged to the sewerage system; 
(vi)  together with the civil engineer, assess and comment on the adequacy of yield and quality of water 
resources  and  present  and  future  demands  ensuring  that  a  full  water  balance  assessment  is 
undertaken for each project city; comment and advise on any anomalies or deficiencies; 
(vii)  assess  the realistic  levels  of  unaccounted-for water  and  recommend actions  to 
minimize losses and wastage; 
(viii)  recommend any change of strategy by government that may be appropriate to 
conserve water resources and also reduce discharges of wastewater; 
(ix)  assess the options for reuse of effluents and recommend suitable corresponding  
treatment standards;  
(x)  in conjunction with the environment specialists, review and comment on the suitability of water 
borehole sources in E’min City and make recommendations for alternatives as required; 
(xi)  develop a water demand management and nonrevenue water management action plan; 
(xii)  review and comment on institutional arrangements relevant to water demand management component, 
water tariff adjustment and public awareness campaign for the project in Tacheng New Area and E’min 
town including the engineering arrangement of reducing nonrevenue water use; 
(xiii)  advise on the standardized application of integrated circuit card metering for all properties and, 
together with the financial analyst, comment on the associated tariff bands to discourage profligate 
water usage; 
(xiv)  advise  on  preparation  of  the  subproject  implementation  schedule  and  detailed 
implementation arrangements, divided into phases as appropriate; 
(xv)  in conjunction with the network modeller, review and comment on the proposed layouts, designs, and 
operational functions of the water supply networks and sewerage systems with particular emphasis on 
network  monitoring  and  control  which,  inter  alia,  will  include  unaccounted-for  water  and  the 
encouragement of water-saving and re-use measures and techniques; 
(xvi)  assist with the assembly of data formatting required for digital network modelling; 
(xvii)  review quantities and costing of proposed water supply sector construction; 
(xviii)  prepare a listing of contract packages by type and budget value;

