(v)  produce inputs to the financial and economic analyses from the demand forecast model;  
(vi)  produce  travel  forecast  data  (annual  average  daily  traffic,  vehicle  type,  peak  hour 
volume)  for  road  engineers  for  deciding  design  specifications  and 
intersection/interchange design; 
(vii)  review  the  economic  analysis  in  the  domestic  feasibility  studies  and  identify  any 
divergence from demand forecast data; 
(viii)  review road and interchange/intersection design on the basis of travel demand outputs;  
(ix)  review the analysis of alternatives for each project component, and ensure that the 
least-cost option is identified; 
(x)  review  the  condition  of  public  transport  services  and  recommend  public  transport 
improvement measures for the project area; 
(xi)  review the condition of NMT facilities and recommend NMT improvement measures for 
the project area; and 
(xii)  review the condition of traffic safety of the study area and recommend traffic safety 
improvement measures for the project area.  

14.  Flood  risk  management  and  river  rehabilitation  specialists  (1.5  person-month, 
international; and 3.0 person-months, national). The expert should have appropriate qualifications 
and at least 12 years (international) and 7 years (national) experience of similar civil engineering 
construction projects. S/he will perform the following tasks: 

(i)  to review flood history, justification, and confirmation of flood protection standard; 
undertake analysis of river embankment design alternatives and assessment of 
nonstructural plans to improve flood risk management, such as flood risk mapping, 
early warning, and evacuation system; 
(ii)  review, comment, and assist in the analysis of ground stability issues particularly 
related to river embankments, cut and fill embankments, pipe trenching, and the 
like; 
(iii)  review  and  advise  on  suitability  of  river  embankment  design  with  particular 
emphasis on bank-toe stability and the avoidance of scour and for ease of future 
maintenance of embankment structure; 
(iv)  critically review proposals for dredging the riverbed and assess the hydrological 
implications  (to  include  an  assessment  of  needs  for  regular  and/or  periodic 
dredging); 
(v)  in conjunction with the environment specialists, review and comment on proposals 
for materials quarries; 
(vi)  in  conjunction  with  the  environment  specialists  assess  and  address  anticipated 
construction-related environmental impacts and risks, (a) impacts of flood control 
works on river hydrology, morphology, and sediment transport, and on livelihood 
systems (including informal urban agriculture and quarry activities in river bed); (b) 
potential downstream impacts of the water supply network and flood control works in 
Tacheng (such as induced flood risk downstream, reduced average and minimum 
water flows); 
(vii)  ensure the eco-friendly bank design for the river flood control to encourage the local 
ecosystem, namely a proper supply of irrigation water for the windbreak trees to be 
considered to avoid the drawing of raw river water; 
(viii)  assist the roads engineers in assessment of suitability of road pavement designs; 
(ix)  assess requirements for foundations of bridges and other structures; and 
(x)  assist the team leader and deputy team leader in preparation of reports.

